WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.120
Okay, so I do workforce training, so if any of you know about this, it's a slightly

00:00:07.120 --> 00:00:10.520
different audience than like university students.

00:00:10.520 --> 00:00:13.720
They get frustrated very easily.

00:00:13.720 --> 00:00:19.160
You know, one of the very first sessions, this has worked millions of times for me,

00:00:19.160 --> 00:00:25.440
but like, you know, I just encountered a learner was just really overwhelmed by RStudio, and

00:00:25.440 --> 00:00:27.680
unfortunately they quit the course.

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:31.559
So this is one of those things that, you know, sometimes you have to go back to the

00:00:31.559 --> 00:00:36.000
drawing board and kind of understand, like, you know, how you can make the experience

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:39.119
better.

00:00:39.119 --> 00:00:42.759
So thanks, Klaus, for introducing WebR and Pyodide.

00:00:42.759 --> 00:00:52.320
So if you want, so I am also going against the live demo thing, but, you know, it's,

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:57.500
this is something that I feel like is just so important to show that you can really.

00:00:58.320 --> 00:00:59.419
So I've got two examples here.

00:00:59.419 --> 00:01:05.580
So one is in R and one is in Python, but you can see that this runs in your browser.

00:01:05.580 --> 00:01:10.220
So I just loaded in some data and I asked for some information.

00:01:10.220 --> 00:01:12.900
It just works in your browser.

00:01:12.900 --> 00:01:18.339
It runs on learners' computers, so you don't have to do, like, shiny hosting or anything

00:01:18.339 --> 00:01:20.519
like that.

00:01:20.519 --> 00:01:26.699
So really, part of my goal for today is to really kind of highlight some use cases for

00:01:26.900 --> 00:01:30.500
WebR and Pyodide that you might not have thought about.

00:01:30.500 --> 00:01:36.820
So my first very use case is really about lowering cognitive load, and we'll talk more

00:01:36.820 --> 00:01:38.980
about that in a second.

00:01:38.980 --> 00:01:44.180
And then, you know, I think one of the things we always want is to give learners freedom,

00:01:44.180 --> 00:01:49.500
but I think you need to give them just enough freedom, like, when they're starting out,

00:01:49.500 --> 00:01:52.059
and so encouraging active learning.

00:01:52.059 --> 00:01:58.260
And then, you know, this is a use case that, like, you know, we found that has been unexpectedly

00:01:58.260 --> 00:02:03.720
useful is, like, actually using WebR to increase social learning and workshops.

00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:08.580
So like I said, with each of these kinds of steps, you're going to increase learner autonomy

00:02:08.580 --> 00:02:10.199
and freedom.

00:02:10.199 --> 00:02:16.699
So I think this is actually a really wonderful technology to think about using in your lessons.

00:02:16.699 --> 00:02:21.020
Okay, so let's talk about lowering cognitive load.

00:02:21.860 --> 00:02:24.940
If you don't know what cognitive load is, here's an illustration.

00:02:24.940 --> 00:02:30.100
So let's talk about, like, you know, a learner as they are kind of sitting there and watching

00:02:30.100 --> 00:02:32.080
you teach.

00:02:32.080 --> 00:02:35.419
So they're thinking about things like, what is R?

00:02:35.419 --> 00:02:37.380
What's a variable?

00:02:37.380 --> 00:02:41.860
They're also thinking about things like, oh, I need to finish that report, or I need to

00:02:41.860 --> 00:02:45.100
pick up my daughter.

00:02:45.179 --> 00:02:50.860
But there's also some extra, extra things, thoughts that are kind of unproductive, like,

00:02:50.860 --> 00:02:53.539
am I doing this right?

00:02:53.539 --> 00:02:56.940
RStudio, like that learner I was talking about, they just didn't get it.

00:02:56.940 --> 00:03:00.500
They got, they basically freaked out and panicked.

00:03:00.500 --> 00:03:06.059
So all of these thoughts in a learner's head is what's called cognitive load.

00:03:06.059 --> 00:03:08.580
So what can we help with?

00:03:08.580 --> 00:03:13.339
There are certain things, like, you know, for example, like finishing the report and

00:03:13.339 --> 00:03:16.940
picking up your daughter, like, we can't help with that.

00:03:16.940 --> 00:03:23.860
But I think, you know, really, you know, these kinds of fear-based thoughts that can prevent

00:03:23.860 --> 00:03:34.539
people from really moving forward and actually learning, we can do a lot of good work with.

00:03:34.539 --> 00:03:39.259
So I am going to posit that fear is part of cognitive load.

00:03:39.259 --> 00:03:42.580
This feeling of, am I doing this right?

00:03:42.580 --> 00:03:48.300
I always get learners who ask, like, you know, what would happen if I did this?

00:03:48.300 --> 00:03:51.899
And my response is always, like, why don't you try it?

00:03:51.899 --> 00:03:56.059
But honestly, like, when you're first starting out, there's that fear of doing something

00:03:56.059 --> 00:04:00.139
wrong, of breaking R.

00:04:00.139 --> 00:04:06.059
And so anything that we can do to kind of alleviate fear and reduce this fear, the less

00:04:06.059 --> 00:04:09.899
cognitive load your learners are going to have.

00:04:09.899 --> 00:04:15.259
So as an example, like, you know, this is where my learner was, you know, we showed

00:04:15.259 --> 00:04:21.220
them RStudio, and, like, very, when you're a brand-new learner to, like, programming

00:04:21.220 --> 00:04:24.700
and everything, this can be very overwhelming.

00:04:24.700 --> 00:04:26.540
Where do you pay attention?

00:04:26.540 --> 00:04:30.260
Like why are there so many windows?

00:04:30.260 --> 00:04:36.040
I mean, we all have gotten used to this, but, you know, especially for people who are just

00:04:36.040 --> 00:04:40.000
kind of approaching this, this can be a lot.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:43.440
So we can really lower this friction for new learners.

00:04:43.440 --> 00:04:46.160
So I'm going to show you an example of an exercise.

00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:54.799
So again, putting ourself in, like, the learner's shoes of, like, someone brand-new, and, you

00:04:54.799 --> 00:05:00.239
know, being able to give feedback, you know, in terms of these interactive exercises.

00:05:00.239 --> 00:05:04.279
Okay, so here's my exercise.

00:05:04.279 --> 00:05:09.720
So just reading it out loud, filter penguins, so it only shows penguins from the island

00:05:09.720 --> 00:05:15.739
of Bisco, and I give a hint, you'll have to use the island variable, and you want to assign

00:05:15.739 --> 00:05:18.140
it to Bisco penguins.

00:05:18.140 --> 00:05:23.880
So here's the corresponding exercise.

00:05:23.880 --> 00:05:30.959
So I'm actually using something called grade this in the background, but if I run this

00:05:30.959 --> 00:05:33.720
code, it's going to give them immediate feedback.

00:05:33.720 --> 00:05:37.839
So you didn't do anything, you need to fill in this.

00:05:37.839 --> 00:05:41.320
So what if I change this?

00:05:41.320 --> 00:05:47.720
I'm not going to try to spell Torgasen live, because it is a difficult word to spell, but,

00:05:47.720 --> 00:05:52.119
like, say I tried the dream island here.

00:05:52.119 --> 00:05:59.799
So this is a little hard to read, but it says, so we did a filtering, but we used kind of

00:05:59.799 --> 00:06:01.320
the wrong word.

00:06:01.359 --> 00:06:12.320
So, but if we change this to Bisco, they immediately get feedback.

00:06:12.320 --> 00:06:19.079
So all of these exercises, there's code in this GitHub repo, and there's also a link

00:06:19.079 --> 00:06:25.559
to the talk here, so all of this, there's examples on how you actually implement all

00:06:25.559 --> 00:06:29.839
of these things.

00:06:29.839 --> 00:06:36.920
So let's talk a little bit about using WebR and PyDyte for in-class exercises.

00:06:36.920 --> 00:06:44.040
I'm a big fan of not making people look up things that were five slides before, so I

00:06:44.040 --> 00:06:49.079
always try to have all of the information that a learner needs available, like, right

00:06:49.079 --> 00:06:51.279
in the exercise.

00:06:51.279 --> 00:06:57.040
Really, you know, it's part, I think WebR is really, and PyDyte is really great at reducing

00:06:57.040 --> 00:07:00.399
friction when practicing.

00:07:00.399 --> 00:07:06.440
I think a lot of us are educational designers, and really the idea of using faded exercise

00:07:06.440 --> 00:07:10.399
design, like, the technology is not the solution, right?

00:07:10.399 --> 00:07:15.519
We have to actually use pedagogical principles to design these exercises.

00:07:15.519 --> 00:07:22.480
So you know, first you kind of have the fill in the blank, and then you slowly give them

00:07:22.480 --> 00:07:29.559
more freedom, and more freedom to actually write their own code.

00:07:29.559 --> 00:07:36.559
And then this is something, if you have used LearnR, or grade this, like, you know, there's

00:07:36.559 --> 00:07:43.959
an option to kind of use these custom grading functions to evaluate code blocks.

00:07:43.959 --> 00:07:47.040
Just a little bit about custom grading functions.

00:07:47.040 --> 00:07:52.200
So this is really the core of, like, you know, using this for effective instructional

00:07:52.200 --> 00:07:58.720
design and learning, is anticipating the possible mistakes and answers, and having a response

00:07:58.720 --> 00:07:59.720
for each.

00:07:59.720 --> 00:08:05.799
So you know, someone might not, their mental model might not be 100% correct, but they

00:08:05.799 --> 00:08:13.279
are able to, giving them kind of specific feedback about that can be really helpful.

00:08:13.279 --> 00:08:19.160
So I don't really have kind of working code here, but there is, these are some examples

00:08:19.160 --> 00:08:24.200
that George has in his Cordo Live documentation.

00:08:24.200 --> 00:08:29.640
So here you can, like, you'd see, you can evaluate kind of results that learners have

00:08:29.640 --> 00:08:36.200
kind of evaluated, and give them specific feedback here.

00:08:36.200 --> 00:08:41.080
As an example, I'm not saying this is the best example, but this is something that we've

00:08:41.080 --> 00:08:44.159
worked on for years and years.

00:08:44.159 --> 00:08:45.799
It's called our R boot camp.

00:08:45.799 --> 00:08:49.679
There's a link right there, and the GitHub repo.

00:08:49.679 --> 00:08:58.080
But you know, this has gone through many iterations, many technologies, and I think with WebR,

00:08:58.080 --> 00:09:01.200
this is kind of where we're going, where we're ending up.

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:07.520
So again, the GitHub repo is there in case you want to take a look at it.

00:09:08.159 --> 00:09:13.400
Okay, so we talked about cognitive load.

00:09:13.400 --> 00:09:18.000
So let's talk about increasing active learning.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:24.520
So if you don't know what active learning is, it's learning by doing, and you know,

00:09:24.520 --> 00:09:29.000
basically providing activities that cement knowledge by application.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:33.760
So you know, it's one thing for us to kind of lecture at people, but when they actually

00:09:33.760 --> 00:09:38.880
try things out, they see, they actually cement the knowledge.

00:09:38.880 --> 00:09:42.960
So I'm going to specifically talk about the idea of meta-learning, which I think is just

00:09:42.960 --> 00:09:48.320
so important for any learners of data science.

00:09:48.320 --> 00:09:51.119
Learning how to learn.

00:09:51.119 --> 00:09:59.640
Okay, so here's an example I'm going to show is about helping learners explore documentation.

00:10:00.640 --> 00:10:04.799
Okay, so look at the documentation for the arrange function.

00:10:04.799 --> 00:10:09.119
So I have it linked here.

00:10:09.119 --> 00:10:12.440
And you can take a look at it.

00:10:12.440 --> 00:10:13.440
I'm not going to.

00:10:13.440 --> 00:10:16.719
I think all of us know how to do that.

00:10:16.719 --> 00:10:21.080
And then how do we change the below code to sort by descending order?

00:10:21.080 --> 00:10:22.080
Anyone?

00:10:22.679 --> 00:10:23.679
Okay.

00:10:23.679 --> 00:10:38.799
So, okay, I'm not going to spend too much time on this, but if you know, you know, have

00:10:38.799 --> 00:10:48.599
to use the DESC function.

00:10:48.599 --> 00:10:51.679
And yeah, so that that looks great.

00:10:51.679 --> 00:10:57.559
The feedback is not visible, but you get the idea.

00:10:57.559 --> 00:11:08.559
Okay, so for active learning, I just think this is like the use case for WebR and Pyedide.

00:11:08.559 --> 00:11:12.960
And like Klaus mentioned, you know, he uses it in his interactive exercises.

00:11:12.960 --> 00:11:18.159
I actually use them in slides, just like I've been showing you.

00:11:18.159 --> 00:11:22.559
And that's just like a great opportunity for people to kind of immediately jump into

00:11:22.559 --> 00:11:25.080
something that you've shown them.

00:11:25.080 --> 00:11:31.239
Okay, so this is the last use case I'm going to talk about, which is like increasing social

00:11:31.239 --> 00:11:32.320
learning.

00:11:32.320 --> 00:11:39.000
This is something we hadn't even thought about, but like kind of once we did it, we were like

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:42.640
very excited about this application.

00:11:42.640 --> 00:11:50.239
So if you don't know what social learning is, really this is a very dry pedagogical

00:11:50.239 --> 00:11:51.239
definition.

00:11:51.239 --> 00:11:55.679
Like it's a cognitive, learning is a cognitive process with social context.

00:11:55.679 --> 00:12:01.239
But really, like it can be summed as we learn better when we learn together and we talk

00:12:01.239 --> 00:12:03.919
about things.

00:12:03.919 --> 00:12:07.000
And that can include discussion with your neighbor.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:13.119
So I'm going to show you kind of an example that we use WebR, Pyedide for social learning.

00:12:13.119 --> 00:12:17.960
These are some examples, and then I'm going to show you a specific example.

00:12:17.960 --> 00:12:22.719
So first is paired programming exercises.

00:12:22.719 --> 00:12:30.119
There is something magical to this in that like, you know, giving learners roles and

00:12:30.119 --> 00:12:36.179
then like having them discuss things seems to increase learning.

00:12:36.179 --> 00:12:40.460
But the one I'm going to show you is really about how you can, about design decisions

00:12:40.460 --> 00:12:44.659
and how design is in the eye of the beholder.

00:12:44.659 --> 00:12:48.219
So this is a workshop that we've done called Better Tables.

00:12:48.219 --> 00:12:55.099
And then I'll talk a little bit about this website that we've kind of put together called

00:12:55.099 --> 00:12:57.739
Data Snacks.

00:12:57.739 --> 00:13:03.820
And we use basically WebR and Pyedide for all of these.

00:13:03.820 --> 00:13:04.820
Okay.

00:13:04.820 --> 00:13:12.780
So when I first encountered ggplot2, I was like, this is exactly like a paper doll.

00:13:12.780 --> 00:13:15.500
Probably dating myself.

00:13:15.500 --> 00:13:20.780
But you know, paper dolls, you can like dress them up in different outfits.

00:13:20.780 --> 00:13:29.260
And I really thought this was a really kind of nice approach to explaining ggplot.

00:13:29.260 --> 00:13:32.840
And again, like, you know, we can talk about design best practices.

00:13:32.840 --> 00:13:37.460
But in the case, I think it's really important for people to discuss what works and what

00:13:37.460 --> 00:13:40.260
doesn't work for them.

00:13:40.260 --> 00:13:45.820
And then, you know, just the ability to share styling code with each other kind of live

00:13:45.820 --> 00:13:50.020
is like really pretty amazing.

00:13:50.020 --> 00:13:53.619
So here's a better plots workshop.

00:13:53.619 --> 00:13:57.659
So we have a TV dataset.

00:13:58.059 --> 00:14:00.260
I'm not showing the plotting code.

00:14:00.260 --> 00:14:08.820
But like, for example, if we run this code here, I've added some annotations.

00:14:08.820 --> 00:14:13.580
And this is a TV shows dataset.

00:14:13.580 --> 00:14:15.739
And all of these kind of different shows.

00:14:15.739 --> 00:14:20.359
And kind of part of the reason I use this for teaching is everyone has an opinion about

00:14:20.359 --> 00:14:22.659
TV shows.

00:14:22.659 --> 00:14:26.820
So it was just kind of a nice thing to kind of include.

00:14:26.979 --> 00:14:34.179
But I also kind of give people the option to kind of add their own annotations to help

00:14:34.179 --> 00:14:36.940
guide people through the visualization.

00:14:36.940 --> 00:14:42.460
I know that this is not a 100% great visualization.

00:14:42.460 --> 00:14:49.619
But just as a demonstration purposes, like, you know, so we've got an annotation for the

00:14:49.619 --> 00:14:51.059
walking dead.

00:14:51.059 --> 00:14:56.340
And like you can see the ratings drop.

00:14:56.340 --> 00:15:02.260
So it's just like, you know, thinking about ways that you can use to like to kind of share

00:15:02.260 --> 00:15:03.260
with people.

00:15:03.260 --> 00:15:04.260
You know?

00:15:04.260 --> 00:15:08.299
I think one of the things that I did with this workshop was really encouraging people

00:15:08.299 --> 00:15:14.400
to like have a comment about like one of the TV shows and kind of share it.

00:15:14.400 --> 00:15:21.919
So this was like unexpectedly really very kind of powerful.

00:15:21.919 --> 00:15:27.479
Because I think it immediately had people kind of sharing code with each other.

00:15:27.479 --> 00:15:35.359
And like, you know, sharing their own kind of fun annotations on the dataset.

00:15:35.359 --> 00:15:37.880
So I don't have time to talk too much about this.

00:15:37.880 --> 00:15:41.599
But this is something we've been playing with at the Hutch.

00:15:41.599 --> 00:15:44.000
So they're called data snacks.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:47.479
Here's an example of like working with parquet files.

00:15:47.479 --> 00:15:50.400
So these are things that we just share with our learners.

00:15:50.400 --> 00:15:56.960
If someone is curious about something, like parquet, we'll write up a data snack for them

00:15:56.960 --> 00:16:00.320
and they can try things out.

00:16:00.320 --> 00:16:06.559
So really you do want to emphasize that WebR and PyEdit as part of the technology spectrum

00:16:06.559 --> 00:16:09.799
don't like replace things.

00:16:09.799 --> 00:16:16.919
Like, you know, for example, like, you know, we start out with WebR and PyEdit, but then

00:16:16.919 --> 00:16:18.719
we have a followup session.

00:16:18.719 --> 00:16:21.640
So it's a little less overwhelming.

00:16:21.640 --> 00:16:29.099
We work on PositCloud with Cordo, probably very similar to what Klaus does.

00:16:29.099 --> 00:16:34.059
And then, you know, we use WebR and PyEdit for in-class exercises.

00:16:34.059 --> 00:16:38.559
So this was actually brought up as a question.

00:16:38.559 --> 00:16:42.280
And I chatted with George a little bit about this.

00:16:42.280 --> 00:16:48.320
Part of the problem is, you know, people want to do tests and assessment with it.

00:16:48.320 --> 00:16:52.679
The problem is that you can see all of the code if you know a little, like, JavaScript

00:16:52.679 --> 00:16:56.919
or how to look into the browser.

00:16:56.919 --> 00:17:04.079
So it is technically difficult to really kind of hide the code and the answers.

00:17:04.079 --> 00:17:10.280
That like I said, if you know anything about a console, you can actually get the answers out.

00:17:10.280 --> 00:17:16.479
George did say if you are interested in this, you can come talk to him.

00:17:16.479 --> 00:17:21.760
It is a possibility, but it is more difficult than just kind of what the current technology

00:17:21.760 --> 00:17:24.160
can do.

00:17:24.160 --> 00:17:31.040
So in conclusion, so WebR and PyEdit is really powerful.

00:17:31.040 --> 00:17:35.599
And like we talked about these various use cases, reducing cognitive load, increasing

00:17:35.599 --> 00:17:40.339
active learning, and increasing social learning.

00:17:40.339 --> 00:17:46.619
And as you give students more and more freedom, they become stronger learners.

00:17:46.619 --> 00:17:48.819
So thanks, everyone.

00:17:48.819 --> 00:17:55.180
Again, especially thank you to George Stagg for all of his work on WebR and Cordo Live

00:17:55.180 --> 00:17:59.939
and for the chat, kind of discussing, like, what it's good at.

00:17:59.939 --> 00:18:00.939
Helped me a lot.

